The Canadian unit of General Motors Corpand the union representing its 40,000 workers remain far apartover local issues in contract talks two days from a threatenedstrike, a union spokesman said.    The deepest divisions appeared to be between General Motorsof Canada Ltd and the Canadian Auto Workers local representing17,000 workers at an assembly plant in Oshawa, Ontario, unionspokesman Wendy Cuthbertson said.    "Local 222 is miles apart," said Cuthbertson. The localassembles full-size pick-up trucks, the Buick Regal and thePontiac 6000.    Local issues there included shift schedules, transfers andworking conditions, union president Bob White said.    The union has threatened to strike at 1000 hrs EDT (1400gmt) on Thursday unless it has reached a tentative settlementwith the automaker by then.    Bargaining was scheduled to continue late into the nightTuesday in an effort to avert a walkout, said Cuthbertson.    On Monday, the union accepted an economic offer from GMCanada that largely matched the pay-and-benefit pattern reachedearlier at Chrysler and Ford in Canada. Reuter&#3;